'''Stevan Dohanos''' (May 18, 1907, [[Lorain, Ohio]] <U+2013> 1994) was an [[artist]] and [[illustrator]] of the [[social realism]] school, best known for his ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]'' covers, and responsible for several of the ''Don't Talk'' set of [[World War II]] [[propaganda]] posters.<ref name="nytimes">{{cite web | url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/06/obituaries/stevan-dohanos-a-stamp-designer-and-illustrator-87.html | title=Stevan Dohanos, A Stamp Designer And Illustrator, 87 | work=The New York Times | date=July 06, 1994 | accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref> He named [[Grant Wood]] and [[Edward Hopper]] as the greatest influences on his painting.
==Life==
Dohanos attended the [[Cleveland Institute of Art|Cleveland School of Art]]. He worked in fine art as well as in commercial art. His easel paintings and prints have been displayed in the [[Cleveland Museum of Art]], [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]], and [[Dartmouth College]]. He was nationally known as an illustrator and magazine cover artist, particularly for his work appearing in ''The Saturday Evening Post'', with over 125 covers. <ref name="Stevan Dohanos ">{{cite web | url=http://www.americanillustration.org/artists/dohanos/dohanos.html | title=Stevan Dohanos | publisher=National Museum of American Illustration, Newport, RI | accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref>

He was a member of the [[National Society of Mural Painters]] and the [[Society of Illustrators]]. He was a founding faculty member of the [[Famous Artists School]] of [[Westport, Connecticut]]. 
In the 1960s he became chairman of the [[Citizens' Stamp Advisory Committee]], which selected art to appear on [[United States]] [[postage stamps]].

